als.com/atlanta/news/2013/04/29/gwcca-committee-approves-360.html?page=all|newspaper=[[American City Business Journals|Atlanta Business Chronicle]]|date=April 29, 2013|access-date=February 21, 2014}}</ref>\n| services engineer = [[WSP Group|WSP]]<ref name=\"engineering\"/>\n| project_manager = Darden & Company <ref>{{cite web |title=Mercedes-Benz Stadium|url=https://www.linkedin.com/company/darden-&-company|publisher=Darden & Company, LLC|accessdate=November 5, 2015}}</ref>\n| general_contractor = HHRM JV (Comprising [[Hunt Construction Group]], Holder Construction, H. J. Russell & Co. & C. D. Moody Construction Co.)<ref name=\"archcon\"/>\n| former_names = New Atlanta Stadium {{small|(Planning/construction)}}\n| tenants = [[Atlanta Falcons]] ([[National Football League|NFL]]) ([[2017 Atlanta Falcons season|2017]]\u2013present)<br />[[Atlanta United FC]] ([[Major League Soccer|MLS]]) ([[2017 Atlanta United FC season|2017]]\u2013present)<br />[[Peach Bowl]] ([[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]) ([[2018 Peach Bowl (January)|2017]]\u2013present)<br />[[Celebration Bowl]] ([[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]) ([[2017 Celebration Bowl|2017]]\u2013present)<br />[[Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game]] ([[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]) (2017\u2013present)<br />[[Georgia High School Association|GHSA]] football championship (2017\u20132018)\n| seating_capacity = American Football: 71,000 <br />{{small|(Expandable to 75,000)}}<br />[[Soccer]]: 42,500<br />{{small|(Expandable to 71,000, standing room to at least 73,019)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atlutd.com/post/2017/07/14/atlanta-united-single-match-tickets-go-sale-mercedes-benz-stadium|title=Atlanta United Single-Match Tickets to Go On-Sale for Mercedes-Benz Stadium|date=July 14, 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ajc.com/sports/atlanta-united-hopes-fan-bring-the-noise-mercedes-benz-stadium/QHD3QGPvJ4YDi9k7aowSxI/|title=Atlanta United hopes fan bring the noise to Mercedes-Benz Stadium|last=Roberson|first=Doug|publisher=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=September 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Atlanta United sets MLS attendance records for single season and game|url=http://www.espnfc.com/atlanta-united-fc/story/3236201/atlanta-united-sets-mls-attendance-records-for-single-season-and-game|accessdate=October 23, 2017|publisher=ESPN FC|date=October 22, 2017|ref=mls-attendance}}</ref><ref name=MLSCup2018>{{cite web |last1=Roberson |first1=Doug |title=Atlanta United sets MLS Cup attendance record |url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/atlanta-sets-mls-cup-attendance-record/lJVEXg0pSHjtlNJ7TM06hK/ |website=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |accessdate=December 9, 2018 |date=December 9, 2018}}</ref>\n| website = {{URL|http://www.mercedesbenzstadium.com|MercedesBenzStadium.com}}\n| record_attendance = American Football: 78,347 {{small|([[2019 Peach Bowl]], December 28, 2019)}} <br />Soccer: 73,019 {{small|([[2018 MLS Cup]], December 8, 2018)}}\n| dimensions = American Football: {{convert|120|x|53.333|yd|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Football Field Dimensions\">{{cite web|last1=Haley|first1=Andy|title=Football Field Dimensions and Goal Post Sizes: A Quick Guide |url=http://www.stack.com/a/the-dimensions-of-a-football-field|publisher=Stack.com|access-date=June 7, 2017}}</ref><br />\nSoccer : {{convert|115|x|75|yd|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"All 22 MLS stadiums\">{{cite web|last1=de los Rios|first1=Gabriel|last2=Calderon|first2=Rudy|title=All 22 MLS stadiums for the 2017 season|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/03/02/all-22-mls-stadiums-2017-season|publisher=Major League Soccer|access-date=March 4, 2017}}</ref>\n| publictransit = '''[[Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority]]'''{{rail color box|system=MARTA|line=Green}}{{rail color box|system=MARTA|line=Blue}}[[Vine City station|Vine City]]<br />[[Dome/GWCC/Philips Arena/CNN Center station|Dome / GWCC / Philips Arena / CNN Center]]\n}}\n\n'''Mercedes-Benz Stadium''' is a [[multi-purpose stadium]] located in [[Atlanta, Georgia]], United States.<ref name=\"mbname\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/sports/football/falcons-officially-announce-mercedes-benz-as-namin/nnP9Y/ | last=Tucker | first=Tim | title=Falcons officially announce Mercedes-Benz as naming rights partner | newspaper=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] | date=August 24, 2015 | access-date=}}</ref> Opened in August 2017 as a replacement for the [[Georgia Dome]], it serves as the home stadium of the [[Atlanta Falcons]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL) and [[Atlanta United FC]] of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS). The stadium is owned by the [[Government of Georgia (U.S. state)|state government of Georgia]] through the [[Georgia World Congress Center|Georgia World Congress Center Authority]], and operated by [[Arthur Blank|AMB Group]], the parent organization of the Falcons and Atlanta United. In June 2016, the total cost of its construction was estimated at [[United States dollar|US$]]1.6 billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/morning_call/2016/06/officials-mercedes-benz-stadium-cost-rises-to-1-6.html|title=Officials: Mercedes-Benz Stadium cost rises to $1.6 billion|date=June 17, 2016|website=bizjournals.com|access-date=April 16, 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe stadium officially opened on August 26, 2017 with a Falcons preseason game against the [[2017 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]], despite the retractable roof system being incomplete at the time.<ref name=\"construction delay\">{{cite web|last1=Tucker|first1=Tim|title=Mercedes-Benz Stadium opening is pushed back again|url=http://www.ajc.com/sports/football/mercedes-benz-stadium-opening-pushed-back-again/wLnfyURmUXYvGcj6iaROMM/|publisher=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"MBS roof incomplete\">{{cite web|last1=McQuade|first1=Alec|title=With roof incomplete, is Mercedes-Benz Stadium safe?|url=http://www.11alive.com/sports/with-roof-incomplete-is-mercedes-benz-stadium-safe/466592533|publisher=WXIA-TV|accessdate=August 28, 2017}}</ref> Several events formerly held at the Georgia Dome moved to Mercedes-Benz Stadium following its completion, including the [[SEC Championship Game|SEC football championship game]] and the [[Peach Bowl]]. In 2018, it hosted the [[2018 College Football Playoff National Championship|College Football Playoff National Championship]] and the [[2018 MLS Cup|MLS Cup]] (as Atlanta United held [[Home advantage|home field advantage]]), and it hosted [[Super Bowl LIII]] in 2019. \n\n==Design==\n[[File:Atlanta Falcons sculpture Mercedes-Benz Stadium 2017-09-19.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Atlanta Falcon sculpture outside the stadium]]\n[[File:Mercedes Benz Stadium interior 2017-08-25 1.jpg|right|thumb|Interior of the stadium in August 2017]]\n\n=== Roof ===\nThe stadium's signature feature is its retractable roof, which features a \"pinwheel\" consisting of eight translucent, triangular panels. Each of the eight panels operates on two straight, parallel rails; one rail is responsible for moving the panel while the other rail stabilizes the panel.<ref name=\"MBS roof incomplete\" /><ref name=\"Newcomb 2014\">{{cite news|url=http://soccer.si.com/2014/04/16/atlanta-mls-expansion-stadium-falcons-arthur-blank/|title=MLS in Atlanta: The $1.2 Billion Stadium Blank\u2019s New Team Will Share with the Falcons|last=Newcomb|first=Tim|date=April 16, 2014|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|access-date=May 14, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140422000618/http://soccer.si.com/2014/04/16/atlanta-mls-expansion-stadium-falcons-arthur-blank/|archivedate=April 22, 2014}}</ref> Closing the roof takes slightly less time than opening the roof, since the roof has to disengage the seals at the start of the opening procedure and slow down towards the end to prevent the panels from getting derailed.<ref name=\"MBS roof opening\" /> When opened, the panels are designed to create the illusion of a bird's wings extended.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.myajc.com/news/sports/falcons-braves-stadium-designs-advance/ngNkF/|title=Falcons, Braves Stadium Designs Advance|last=Tucker|first=Tim|date=June 21, 2014|newspaper=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|access-date=February 13, 2015}}</ref>  \n\nArchitect Bill Johnson explained that the circular opening in the roof was inspired by the Roman [[Pantheon, Rome|Pantheon]] (\"Pantheon\" was also the working name for the building design). The roof was designed to be made of a clear, lightweight polymer material that can adjust its opacity to control light, and much of the exterior is clear polymer or glass to allow views to the outside. The middle concourse and upper bowl were eliminated in the east end zone to allow for an unobstructed view of the Atlanta skyline.<ref name=\"Newcomb 2014\" />\n\nBelow the roof is the \"Halo\", an {{convert|58|by|1100|ft|m|adj=on}}, ring-shaped [[Jumbotron|video board]] around its rim. Covering a total area of {{convert|62,350|sqft}}, it was described by manufacturer [[Daktronics]] as being \"three times as large as the current largest single display board in the NFL\" installed at [[EverBank Field]] in Jacksonville (also built by Daktronics).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.myajc.com/sports/mercedes-benz-stadium-video-board-could-game-changer/RcMJYsB3XRTmMV9HF5TlyH/|title=Mercedes-Benz Stadium\u2019s video board could be a game changer|work=[[myAJC]]|access-date=February 3, 2019|language=en|quote=Called the \u201chalo board\u201d by everyone involved in the project, the 360-degree screen is 58 feet tall and 1,075 feet in circumference, totaling 62,350 square feet of light-emitting diodes.}}</ref> Daktronics also installed more than {{convert|20,000|sqft|m2}} of other LED boards, including field-level advertising boards for soccer games.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/sports/football/falcons-hire-firm-to-build-nfls-largest-video-boar/nj2DH/|title=Falcons Hire Firm to Build NFL\u2019s Largest Video Board|last=Tucker|first=Tim|date=January 30, 2015|newspaper=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|access-date=February 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe stadium's roof can be kept open under light precipitation, as the electrical systems for all video boards in the stadium are outdoor-rated, and the field has a drainage system. AMB Group senior executive Mike Egan went as far as describing Mercedes-Benz Stadium as \"an outdoor stadium with a roof over it\" due to these characteristics, but that other factors such as humidity and outside temperatures would be taken into consideration on whether or not the roof would be opened.<ref name=\"MBS roof opening\" />\n\n=== Interior ===\nThe stadium also includes features specific for college football use. It opened with two oversized locker rooms, each capable of housing 100 players, reflecting the much larger size of college football rosters compared to those of the NFL. However, the stadium did not initially include another feature important in that context\u2014staircases connecting the seats to the field, making it difficult for [[Marching band|bands]] to enter the field for halftime shows (most NFL teams, including the Falcons, do not have bands).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/21945677/college-football-playoff-national-championship-home-atlanta|title=How Atlanta became the capital of college football|last=Maisel|first=Ivan|authorlink=Ivan Maisel|date=January 3, 2018|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref> It also has a [[Soccer-specific stadium|soccer-specific]] configuration, with retractable lower bowl seats to widen the field, and mechanized curtains that limit the capacity to about 42,500.<ref name=\"Straus 2014\">{{cite news|url=http://soccer.si.com/2014/04/18/atlanta-mls-jim-smith-arthur-blank-expansion/|title=Former Crew GM, Current Falcons VP Confident Blank, MLS Will Be Fruitful Combo|last=Straus|first=Brian|date=April 18, 2014|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|access-date=May 14, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140423002725/http://soccer.si.com/2014/04/18/atlanta-mls-jim-smith-arthur-blank-expansion/|archivedate=April 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe stadium incorporates contemporary art into its interior and exterior design, with over 180 commissioned works, including pieces by Nari Ward, Hank Willis Thomas, and Steven and William Ladd. The centerpiece of the art collection is G\u00e1bor Mikl\u00f3s Sz\u0151ke's stainless steel sculpture ''The Atlanta Falcon'', which the artist said is the largest freestanding bird sculpture in the world. The falcon, perched atop a {{convert|13|foot|m}} tall bronze football, is {{convert|41|feet|m}} high with a wingspan of {{convert|70|feet|m}}. The over {{convert|73,000|lb|kg}} artwork stands in front of the stadium, and as tall as a four-story building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/atlanta-falcons-mercedes-benz-stadium-1041056|title=In Atlanta's New $1.5 Billion Football Stadium, the High-Priced Artworks Will Outnumber the Players \u2013 artnet News|date=August 7, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== Amenities ===\nThe upper concourse includes an area known as the \"100 Yard Club\", a concession and gathering area that stretches the length of the football field. Other noted areas include the \"[[AT&T]] Perch\"\u2014a gathering area with televisions and video walls airing other games (designed as being of interest to [[Fantasy football (gridiron)|fantasy football]] players), and the \"[[Budweiser]] [[Beer garden|Biergarten]]\". Several \"neighborhood bars\" also operate within the stadium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/gathering-spaces-are-big-part-mercedes-benz-stadium-game-plan/5I2MIHbhJQpH9CziQwzuPP/|title=Gathering spaces are a big part of Mercedes-Benz Stadium\u2019s game plan|last=Tucker|first=Tim|date=|website=AJC|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myajc.com/news/sports/falcons-braves-stadium-designs-advance/ngNkF/?icmp=ajc_internallink_invitationbox_apr2013_ajcstubtomyajcpremium#a09dff25.3728029.735543|title=Falcons, Braves stadium designs advance|author=Tim Tucker|date=June 21, 2014|work=[[MyAJC]]|access-date=April 11, 2017}}</ref> The former Georgia Dome site between the stadium and the [[Georgia World Congress Center]] was redeveloped as \"[[The Home Depot]] Backyard\"\u2014an {{convert|11|acre|||abbr=|adj=on}} green space used as a [[Tailgate party|tailgating]] area. It also features a 3-tier, dual-level, shaded deck pavilion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/home-depot-backyard-opens-georgia-dome-site/S6GKHILsCpeT4QDLIrZvyJ/|title=Home Depot Backyard opens on Georgia Dome site|last=Tim|first=Tucker|website=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|language=English|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> \n\nFor its concessions, Mercedes-Benz Stadium focused primarily on the quality and speed of service, variety, and pricing; the stadium includes at least 670 points-of-sale, and has a policy of \"fan first pricing\" for all concessions\u2014with lower menu prices in comparison to other sports facilities during all events regardless of stature, such as a [[United States dollar|$]]2 beverage cup with free refills, and a $5 beer. To increase the speed of service, all items were priced at whole dollars only, with the 9.3% [[Sales taxes in the United States|sales tax]] already included in the posted menu prices (rather than added at the time of purchase ).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/mercedes-benz-stadium-will-convert-cashless-operation/7GdA0UNpqYUrB5b4dpdNZI/|title=Mercedes-Benz Stadium will convert to cashless operation|last=Tim|first=Tucker|date=March 7, 2019|website=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> The practice helped to increase the venue's revenue, as the lower prices have been offset by increased spending on concessions by attendees.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nIn March 2019, following a trial in 2018, the stadium became one of the first major professional sports venues in the United States to only accept [[Cashless society|\"cashless\"]] payment methods for transactions at concessions inside the stadium, such as credit or debit cards, and [[mobile payment]]s. This only applies to concessions; cash is still accepted for ticket sales and any third-party merchandising that may operate during events, and kiosks are provided for loading cash onto prepaid debit cards (with no transaction fees charged). At the same time, the stadium raised all menu prices, by adding tax at the time of purchase but maintaining the same posted price values as before (besides five items, such as hot dogs, whose list prices were discounted by 50 cents).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nTo reflect local culture, the stadium also partnered with Atlanta-based restaurants, chains, and chefs to have presences as concessions under the \"Best of Atlanta\" banner, including [[Chick-fil-A]],  [[The Varsity]], [[Kevin Gillespie (chef)|Kevin Gillespie]], and others. In consistence with the fan first pricing policy, these partners agreed to not [[Markup (business)|mark up]] their prices in comparison to their standalone locations.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/atlanta-restaurants/concession-prices-mercedes-benz-stadium-are-something-cheer-about/ujjOXV2crKjUmChtjaCz9K/|title=Concession prices at Mercedes-Benz Stadium are something to cheer about|last=Figueras|first=Ligaya|date=|website=ajc|language=english|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com:443/en/Journal/Issues/2018/01/29/Franchises/Atlanta.aspx|title=\u2018Fan first\u2019 pays off for Falcons, United|last=|first=|date=January 28, 2018|website=Sports Business Journal|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> As with all other locations under a long-standing corporate policy, the Chick-fil-A [[Chick-fil-A#Sunday closure|does not operate on Sundays]], with no exception, even though the stadium's main tenant primarily plays on Sundays. During Sunday events, the Chick-fil-A stand is replaced by an unbranded \"Fries Up\" stand operated by the stadium's concessionary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/the-falcons-billion-dollar-stadium-will-have-a-chick-fil-a-thats-almost-never-open/|title=The Falcons' billion-dollar stadium will have a Chick-fil-A that's almost never open|website=CBSSports.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/super-bowl/2019/01/22/chick-fil-a-closed-super-bowl-sunday-stadium-location-atlanta/2650539002/|title=Chick-fil-A location at Mercedes-Benz Stadium isn't open on Super Bowl Sunday|last1=Gardner|first1=Steve|date=January 22, 2019|work=USA Today|accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== Planning ===\nIn May 2010, it was reported by multiple news outlets that the Atlanta Falcons were interested in replacing the [[Georgia Dome]] with a newly constructed open-air stadium, although at the time it was planned to retain the Georgia Dome to continue hosting non-NFL events.<ref>{{cite web |title=McKay: Hope New Stadium by 2015|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=5209110|work=[[ESPN]]|date=May 21, 2010|accessdate=September 9, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"ajc1\">{{cite news |title=Falcons Prefer New Open-Air Stadium, Downtown|first1=D. Orlando|last1=Ledbetter|first2=Leon|last2=Stafford|url=http://www.ajc.com/sports/falcons-prefer-new-open-531016.html|newspaper=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=May 19, 2010|accessdate=September 9, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Falcons Want Open Air Stadium North of GWCC|first1=J. Scott|last1=Trubey|first2=Maria|last2=Saporta, Maria|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/stories/2010/05/17/daily40.html|newspaper=[[American City Business Journals|Atlanta Business Chronicle]]|date=May 19, 2010|accessdate=September 9, 2012}}</ref> The team was pursuing a new stadium because of the team's desire to play outdoors, as well as Falcons team owner [[Arthur Blank]]'s interest in hosting another [[Super Bowl]].<ref name=\"ajc1\" /> The stadium was also pursued as a possible bid for a venue of an upcoming [[FIFA World Cup]].[[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]]-based architectural firm [[Populous (company)|Populous]] released comprehensive plans for the proposed stadium in February 2011.<ref name=\"plan\">{{cite web |title=Master Plan Phase III \u2013 New Open Air NFL Stadium|url=http://www.blogandtackle.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/AtlantaStadiumProposal02-11_Part1.pdf|publisher=Populous|accessdate=September 9, 2012}}</ref> Populous' early cost estimate for the project was US$700 million.<ref>{{cite news |title=Falcons' Push for Open-Air Stadium Gets Lift|first1=Leon|last1=Stafford|first2=D. Orlando|last2=Ledbetter|first3=Jeremiah|last3=McWilliams|url=http://www.ajc.com/business/falcons-push-for-open-848736.html|newspaper=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=February 22, 2011|accessdate=September 9, 2012}}</ref> According to the master plan, the stadium would have a maximum capacity of 71,000, but can expand to 75,000 for special events such as the Super Bowl. It will also feature multiple club levels, suites and exhibition area.<ref name=\"plan\" />\n\nIn April 2012, Populous released a new price estimate of US$947.7 million, which was significantly higher than the previous proposal of US$700 million.<ref name=\"ajc2\">{{cite news |title=New Falcons Stadium Cost Could Exceed $1 billion|first1=Leon|last1=Stafford|first2=Tim |last2=Tucker|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/new-falcons-stadium-cost-1426844.html|newspaper=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=April 27, 2012|accessdate=September 9, 2012}}</ref> In April 2012, ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' reported that if a deal was reached, the new stadium's construction would be expected to begin in 2014, with the Falcons to begin regular-season play in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |title=New Stadium Plan: Retractable Roof, Demolish Dome|first1=Leon|last1=Stafford|first2=Tim|last2=Tucker|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/sports/football/new-stadium-plan-retractable-roof-demolish-dome-1/nQTK4/|newspaper=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=April 25, 2012|accessdate=March 19, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"fox\">{{cite news |title=Atlanta Falcons seeking $1 billion retractable-roof stadium|url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2012/04/26/atlanta-falcons-seeking-1-billion-retractable-roof-stadium/|publisher=[[Fox News]] |date=April 26, 2012|accessdate=September 9, 2012}}</ref> The proposed location of the new stadium is a large parking lot in Atlanta's [[English Avenue and Vine City|Vine City]] neighborhood, which is less than a mile north of the Georgia Dome's current location.<ref>{{cite news |title=Neighbors of Potential New Stadium Seek Voice|first=Leon|last=Stafford|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/neighbors-of-potential-new-1447239.html|newspaper=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=May 26, 2012|accessdate=August 8, 2012}}</ref> Once construction is complete, the Georgia Dome would subsequrently be demolished.<ref name=\"fox\" />\n\nOn August 24, ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' reported that an official deal could be reached on the construction of a new stadium by the end of 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stadium Deal Could Be Done by End of Year|first1=Leon|last1=Stafford|first2=Tim |last2=Tucker|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/business/stadium-deal-could-be-done-by-end-of-year/nRMRC/|newspaper=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=August 24, 2012|accessdate=September 9, 2012}}</ref> They also reported on September 10 that [[Atlanta]] mayor [[Kasim Reed]] said site improvements could likely bump the total cost to US$1.2 billion; however, that does not increase the actual building cost, which still remains at an estimated US$948 million.<ref>{{cite news |title=Reed: Work Around New Falcons Stadium Could Boost Cost to $1.2 Billion|first1=Jeremiah|last1=McWilliams|first2=Tim|last2=Tucker|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/news/reed-workb-around-new-falcons-stadium-could-boost-c/nR7P8/|newspaper=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=September 10, 2012|accessdate=September 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn December 10, the [[Georgia World Congress Center Authority]], in a unanimous decision, approved the blueprint and most of the agreement terms for the new stadium plans. According to ''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' article, the term sheet is non-binding and changes could be made at any time as regards stadium construction. Stadium location, however, is yet to be worked out; proposed locations being reported are within walking distance of the Georgia Dome, with one site located one-half mile north, and the other one block directly south, at the one of the stadium's existing parking lots.<ref>{{cite news |title=GWCCA Approves Falcons Stadium Blueprint |first=Leon|last=Stafford|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/news/gwcca-approves-falcons-stadium-blueprint/nTRYP/|newspaper=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=December 10, 2012|accessdate=January 10, 2013}}</ref> The project made national headlines for the first time in 2012 on December 15, with team owner Arthur Blank stating in ''[[The New York Times]]'' that he would rather have a new stadium be constructed than a \"remodeling job\" of the Georgia Dome.<ref>{{cite news |title=Falcons Seek New Dome, Not Atlanta Fixer-Upper|first=Mike |last=Tierney|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/16/sports/football/atlanta-falcons-not-interested-in-fixer-upper-seek-a-new-stadium.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 15, 2012|accessdate=January 10, 2013}}</ref> During a January 10, 2013 press conference, mayor Reed expressed his optimism and confidence in the construction of the new stadium; he also mentioned the possibility of the new stadium helping the city compete for its first [[Major League Soccer]] team.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mayor Reed confident Atlanta will get new stadium|first=Jeremiah|last=McWilliams|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/news/mayor-reed-confident-atlanta-will-get-new-stadium/nTsKp/|newspaper=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=January 10, 2013|accessdate=January 10, 2013}}</ref>[[File:Overhead shot of Georgia Dome, New Falcons stadium construction site April 25, 2014.jpg|right|thumb|Aerial photo showing land next to Georgia Dome cleared for construction of the new stadium.]]\n\nOn March 7, 2013, the Falcons and the city of Atlanta agreed to build the new downtown stadium. The maximum public contribution for the project was US$200 million, coming from the hotel-motel tax in Atlanta and unincorporated Fulton County. The Atlanta City Council officially approved the stadium on March 19, 2013. The council voted, 11\u20134, in favor of the use of city hotel-motel taxes to pay US$200 million toward construction costs and potentially several times that toward costs of financing, maintaining and operating the stadium through 2050.<ref>{{cite news |title=Atlanta council clears stadium plan|first1=Ernie|last1=Suggs|first2=Tim|last2=Tucker |url=http://www.ajc.com/news/news/local/key-stadium-vote-could-come-today/nWwwt/|newspaper=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=March 19, 2013|accessdate=March 19, 2013}}</ref> On May 21, 2013, the NFL approved a US$200 million loan to the Falcons organization for the purpose of building the stadium.<ref name=\"nflloan\">{{cite news|last1=Wilner|first1=Barry|title=Falcons get $200 million NFL loan for stadium|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/may/21/falcons-get-200-million-nfl-loan-for-stadium/|accessdate=April 21, 2015|work=Washington Post|agency=Associated Press|date=May 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Falcons unveiled a conceptual design for the new stadium on June 18, 2013, with a proposed capacity of 70,000 spectators, 7,500 club seats, and 180 luxury suites.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nfl-shutdown-corner/falcons-initial-approval-forward-futuristic-stadium-design-212055897.html |title=Falcons have initial approval to go forward with futuristic stadium design |first=Doug |last=Farrar |work=Shutdown Corner |publisher=[[Yahoo! Sports]] |date=June 18, 2013 |accessdate=November 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nArthur Blank indicated the groundbreaking of the stadium would be conducted the last week of March 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=Atlanta Falcons Owner Arthur Blank Said New $1 Billion Stadium Development Is \u2018in a Geally Good Place\u2019|first=Maria|last=Saporta|url=http://saportareport.com/blog/2013/10/atlanta-falcons-owner-arthur-blank-said-new-football-stadium-project-is-in-a-really-good-place/|work=Saporta Report|date=October 14, 2013|accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Blank: Falcons Stadium Groundbreaking Week of March 31|first=Carla|last=Caldwell|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/morning_call/2013/10/blank-falcons-stadium-groundbreaking.html|newspaper=[[American City Business Journals|Atlanta Business Chronicle]]|date=October 14, 2013|accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Blank: Falcons Stadium Groundbreaking Week of March 31|url=http://newstadium.atlantafalcons.com/2013/10/16/blank-falcons-stadium-groundbreaking-week-of-march-31/|publisher=Atlanta Falcons|date=October 16, 2013|accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref> Just after [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] Drive was closed permanently, the Mount Vernon Baptist Church held its last Sunday service on March 9 before the historic church was [[demolish]]ed. Friendship Baptist, the birthplace of both Spelman College and Morehouse College, was also demolished and relocated to make room for the stadium. Due to legal issues surrounding the issuing of bonds, the stadium did not break ground until May 19, 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=At stadium groundbreaking, Blank lobbies for a Super Bowl|first=Tim|last=Tucker|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/sports/football/at-stadium-groundbreaking-blank-lobbies-for-a-supe/nfzg3/|newspaper=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=May 19, 2014|accessdate=May 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://wabe.org/post/judge-hears-arguments-legal-challenge-falcons-stadium-financing|title=Judge Hears Arguments In Legal Challenge Of Falcons Stadium Financing|last=Shapiro|first=Jonathan|date=April 10, 2014|work=[[WABE]]|accessdate=May 14, 2014|location=Atlanta}}</ref>[[File:Mercedes-Benz Stadium Drone Fly-Over.webm|thumb|Construction site in November 2015.]]\n<br />\n\n=== Construction delays, opening ===\n[[File:Georgia Dome 2017.JPG|thumb|The Georgia Dome (right) and Mercedes-Benz Stadium on July 2, 2017]]\n[[File:Mercedes-Benz Stadium with the Georgia Dome remains in the foreground (27663350329).jpg|thumb|right|The remains of Georgia Dome with the Mercedes-Benz Stadium in the background.]]\nThe stadium's projected opening date was delayed three times due to the complexity of the eight-panel retractable roof. The stadium was originally intended to open on March 1, 2017; however, the opening date was later delayed to June 1, 2017, then to July 30, 2017, and then to August 26, 2017. Steve Cannon, CEO of the Atlanta Falcons' parent company AMB Group, stated that the Falcons' preseason schedule and the Chick-fil-a Kickoff Games would not be affected by the new opening date; however, three of Atlanta United's matches would be affected. The July 30 game against [[Orlando City SC]] was moved to Atlanta United's interim home of [[Bobby Dodd Stadium]] for July 29 while two home matches scheduled in August were moved to later dates. Additionally, the Georgia Dome's demolition was put on hold until the new stadium's [[certificate of occupancy]] could be issued.<ref name=\"construction delay\"/> On June 9, 2017, stadium officials announced that they were confident that Mercedes-Benz Stadium would open as scheduled, and demolition of the Georgia Dome had resumed, and the Dome was imploded on the morning of November 20, 2017.<ref name=\"Dome Implosion Date Set\">{{cite news|last1=Tucker|first1=Tim|title=Georgia Dome implosion date set|url=http://www.ajc.com/sports/football/georgia-dome-implosion-date-set/uJTjDe07LxuGOU5xyKBt6H/|accessdate=July 5, 2017|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution}}</ref>\n\nOn July 25, 2017, stadium officials reported that the roof would be in the closed position during the Falcons' preseason games and the [[Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game|Chick-fil-A Kickoff]] games while contractors continue to fine tune the roof to allow all eight panels to work in sync. Falcons' President Rich McKay also stated that the roof would remain closed whenever outside temperatures exceed {{convert|80|F|C|0}}.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McClure|first1=Vaughn|title=Falcons' stadium roof will be closed for home opener vs. Packers|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/20157717/atlanta-falcons-mercedes-benz-stadium-roof-closed-preseason-start-regular-season|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=July 26, 2017}}</ref> On August 16, 2017, [[WXIA-TV|WXIA]] reported that construction of the retractable roof system was intentionally delayed by stadium and construction officials to ensure the roof's long term operability and to ensure that other parts of the stadium would be completed on time.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McQuade|first1=Alec|title=Exclusive: Mercedes-Benz Stadium officials reveal why retractable roof is delayed|url=http://www.11alive.com/sports/exclusive-mercedes-benz-stadium-stadium-officials-reveal-why-retractable-roof-is-delayed/464595549|publisher=WXIA-TV|accessdate=August 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn September 10, 2017, the Falcons announced that, contrary to earlier plans, the stadium roof would in fact be open during the Falcons home opener on September 17 against the [[Green Bay Packers]] if weather permitted.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tucker|first1=Tim|title=Falcons plan to open roof for home opener if weather cooperates|url=http://www.ajc.com/sports/falcons-plan-open-roof-for-home-opener-weather-cooperates/qCexvumOwrWkkNRs2g7YQO/|publisher=AJC|accessdate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> On October 6, 2017, stadium officials announced that the roof would be opened, weather permitting, for Atlanta United's regular season finale against [[Toronto FC]] on October 22; stadium officials also stated that the roof would remain closed for the remainder of the Falcons' regular season as well as for any home matches hosted by Atlanta United during the [[2017 MLS Cup Playoffs]] as contractors continue to worked on fully mechanizing the roof.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tucker|first1=Tim|title=Plan: Stadium roof will be closed for rest of Falcons season, open for one soccer game|url=http://www.ajc.com/sports/plan-stadium-roof-will-closed-for-rest-falcons-season-open-for-one-soccer-game/eFcG6uolRi3qcGatIffwxL/|accessdate=October 10, 2017|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=October 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Additional construction and renovations ===\n\nHoping to address concerns of overcrowding at the ingress and egress areas of the stadium, stadium officials announced that they plan to add several more doors to the stadium. Overcrowding and congestion was a frequent concern and complaint from fans attending major events during the stadium's first year of operation. Fans attending the [[College Football Playoff National Championship|College Football National Championship]] game reported significant delays in both entering and exiting the stadium, with some reporting wait times that exceeded 45 minutes to get out of the stadium at the completion of the game.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://amp.wsbtv.com/sports/mercedes-benz-stadium-will-add-more-exit-doors/691440162?ecmp=wsbtv_social_twitter_sfp|title=Mercedes-Benz Stadium will add more exit doors|last=EndPlay|date=January 30, 2018|work=WSBTV|access-date=January 30, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==== Pedestrian bridge ====\nA pedestrian bridge was planned but not originally opened when the stadium first opened. The bridge was completed in January 2019 at a cost of ~$33 million.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Keenan |first1=Sean |title=Downtown\u2019s Northside Drive pedestrian bridge project cost surpasses $33M |url=https://atlanta.curbed.com/2019/7/24/20708582/downtown-northside-drive-pedestrian-bridge-cost-renew-atlanta |website=Curbed Atlanta |publisher=Vox Media |accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref> It features a serpentine like structure on both ends, and a cover over the main span with customizable LEDs. The bridge connects gameday parking lots and the [[Vine City station|Vine City MARTA Station]] to the northwest side of the stadium and The Home Depot Backyard, allowing pedestrians to avoid crossing the busy, 6 lane [[Northside Drive]].\n\nThe bridge is criticized for its immense cost, originally only planned to cost $13 million, but swelling to $33 million in part to expedite construction so it would be completed for [[Super Bowl LIII]]. However, the bridge was not open for the Super Bowl as it was deemed a security risk.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wenk |first1=Amy |title=$20+ million pedestrian bridge to Mercedes-Benz Stadium to be closed for Super Bowl |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/news/2019/01/28/20-million-pedestrian-bridge-to-mercedes-benz.html |website=Atlanta Business Chronicle |publisher=American City Business Journals |accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref> The bridge is also criticized for its inequity and siphoning funds from the 2016 Renew Atlanta TSPLOST; the bridge was not originally on the project lists, so other projects originally on the list had to be removed. Critics argue the original projects would have accomplished more and served more people.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Keenan |first1=Sean |title=Report: Downtown pedestrian bridge shows city not built to foster equality |url=https://atlanta.curbed.com/2019/8/12/20801823/downtown-mercedes-benz-pedestrian-bridge-equity |website=Curbed Atlanta |publisher=Vox Media |accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mercedes-Benz Stadium Pedestrian Bridge.jpg|The ~$33 million pedestrian bridge on the west side of the stadium, spanning over Northside Drive.|thumb]]\n\n==== Playing surface ====\nOn February 7, 2019, stadium officials stated that the artificial turf would be replaced prior to the Falcons' 2019 season as part of nearly $2 million in capital improvements to the stadium; stadium officials also noted that the turf would be replaced approximately every two years given the number of events, both private and public, held annually at Mercedes-Benz Stadium.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tucker |first1=Tim |title=Mercedes-Benz Stadium turf will be replaced |url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/mercedes-benz-stadium-turf-will-replaced/PcS9B1tDK4d4cPqJWdsHkJ/ |accessdate=February 9, 2019 |work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |date=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Retractable roof ===\nSeveral reports of the roof leaking during the stadium's inaugural season caused some issues for the stadium's design team. During the [[College football National Championship Game|College Football National Championship Game]] in January 2018, several media outlets reported a significant leak that appeared to be occurring just over the field of play near the 25-yard line. Bill Hancock, College Football Playoff Executive Director, said that he and his team had been made aware of the issue concerning water leaking from the roof and that he believed that the issue did not affect the field of play during the game. Neither team competing in the game reported any issues with the playing surface.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.fox5atlanta.com/news/when-will-mercedes-benz-stadiums-roof-fully-work|title=When will Mercedes-Benz Stadium's roof fully work?|last=FOX|work=WAGA|access-date=January 31, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nStadium officials clarified after the initial leaks that were reported back in October 2017 that the issue was not a \"leak\" but rather a \"few drops of water\" that were falling from the roof around isolated parts of the stadium. Officials stated that the issue was due to the fact that the roof was still not fully mechanized yet, and that the issues would be fixed before the Falcons' 2018 season. They also stated that the issues were common for newly constructed stadiums with retractable roofs.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n[[File:Mercedes-Benz Stadium Roof Atlanta United 2018-10-21 - 17 14.jpg|thumb|upright|Mercedes-Benz Stadium roof in October 2018]]\n\nSince the retractable roof was one of the major features and design points of the stadium, some of the problems with the roof were magnified in the stadium's first year of operation. The roof, which is supposed to open in as little as 12 minutes with the push of a button, was not fully operational by the time the stadium's primary tenants, the [[Atlanta Falcons]] and the [[Atlanta United FC]], seasons began. The roof was required to be mechanically opened, which was a very time-consuming process. As such, the roof was only opened twice in its first year of use, once for an Atlanta Falcons game \u2013 a ''[[NBC Sunday Night Football|Sunday Night Football]]'' game against the Green Bay Packers on September 17, 2017 and a nationally televised MLS soccer game, when the Atlanta United FC hosted [[Toronto FC]] in a sold-out game of more than 70,000 fans on October 22, 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wabe.org/mercedes-benz-stadium-roof-open-1-2017-event/|title=Mercedes-Benz Stadium Roof To Open For Only 1 More 2017 Event {{!}} 90.1 FM WABE|date=October 9, 2017|work=90.1 FM WABE|access-date=January 31, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nFalcons president Rich McKay told the ''Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' that he expected all issues with the roof to be completely resolved before the 2018 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/sports/falcons-expect-mercedes-benz-stadium-roof-open-2018/nmZV9ohkLTN3UJcr0Hpe5O/|title=Falcons expect Mercedes-Benz Stadium roof to open in 2018|last=Makrides|first=Alex|website=ajc|language=English|access-date=January 31, 2018}}</ref> On May 29, 2018, the roof was opened for the first time since October 2017 for construction purposes. Stadium officials stated that the roof would be open for 10 days, regardless of weather, to complete work on automating the roof. After the 10-day construction period, an unspecified time frame would be required for final commissioning work, after of which, operation of the roof would be turned over to stadium officials.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tucker |first1=Tim |title=Mercedes-Benz Stadium roof is open |url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/mercedes-benz-stadium-roof-open/kAEqWU0BlZZ9zKfylMrXBJ/ |accessdate=June 3, 2018 |work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution}}</ref> Work on the roof was completed on July 14, 2018.<ref name=\"MBS roof opening\">{{cite news |last1=Tucker |first1=Tim |title=A guide to when Mercedes-Benz Stadium roof could be open |url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/mercedes-benz-stadium-roof-sorting-through-questions-before-sunday-showcase/HHbBmGWVphQY4djEwuiKhP/?icmp=np_inform_variation-test |accessdate=August 4, 2018 |work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |date=July 27, 2018}}</ref> On July 25, 2018, in a demonstration to members of the media, the roof was opened and closed for the first time as intended, with both procedures taking approximately eight minutes each.<ref name=\"MBS roof complete\">{{cite news |last1=Tucker |first1=Tim |title=Mercedes-Benz Stadium roof opened in about eight minutes |url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/mercedes-benz-stadium-roof-opened-about-eight-minutes/3fTRqV1w31y64UY76DoABO/?icmp=np_inform_variation-test |accessdate=July 26, 2018 |work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |date=July 25, 2018}}\n</ref>\n\n==Costs and funding==\nIn December 2014, the Georgia World Congress Center's board of governors approved a resolution to raise the cost of the stadium to US$1.2 billion. The stadium was initially slated to cost US$1 billion, then rose to US$1.2 billion in October 2013.<ref>{{cite news |title=Atlanta Falcons stadium's Cost Will 'rise up' to $1.4 Billion|first1=Maria|last1=Saporta|first2=Amy|last2=Wenk|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/news/2014/12/02/atlanta-falcons-stadiums-cost-could-rise-to-1-4.html?page=all|newspaper=[[American City Business Journals|Atlanta Business Chronicle]]|date=December 2, 2014|accessdate=February 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe city has agreed to contribute US$200 million in stadium bonds, but with additional tax revenues<ref>{{cite web|title=Falcons Stadium Cost to Taxpayers, Counting Hidden Subsidies: $554 Million|first=Neil|last=deMause|url=http://www.fieldofschemes.com/2013/03/18/4735/falcons-stadium-cost-to-taxpayers-counting-hidden-subsidies-554-million/|work=Field of Schemes|date=March 18, 2013|accessdate=February 5, 2015}}</ref> and with the state of Georgia contributing US$40 million for parking expansion, public spending is expected to eclipse US$700 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/sep/29/why-are-georgia-taxpayers-paying-700m-for-a-new-nfl-stadium|title=Why are Georgia taxpayers paying $700m for a new NFL stadium?|last=deMause|first=Neil|date=2017-09-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-07-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Falcons Stadium Subsidy Nearing $600m Thanks to State-Funded Parking Garage|first=Neil|last=deMause|url=http://www.fieldofschemes.com/2015/01/20/8387/falcons-stadium-subsidy-nearing-600m-thanks-to-state-funded-parking-garage/|work=Field of Schemes|date=January 20, 2015|accessdate=February 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, the Falcons announced the sale of [[personal seat license]]s (PSL) costing up to US$45,000 per seat, depending on the section of the stadium. The most expensive tickets are priced at US$385 per game, in addition to one-time PSL fees, for the first three years. The total revenue generated from PSL sales was $273 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/football/defaults-falcons-psls-reach-million-records-show/YtQHnTqSsn3PPOCPLwQrOJ/|title=Defaults on Falcons\u2019 PSLs reach $30 million, records show|last=Tim Tucker|first=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|website=ajc|language=English|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Falcons Announce Controversial Ticket Pricing for New Stadium|url=http://www.wsbtv.com/news/news/local/falcons-club-seat-psls-10000-45000/njjPq/|work=[[WSB-TV|WSB]]|location=Atlanta|date=January 8, 2015|accessdate=February 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn August 21, 2015, the ''Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' reported that [[Mercedes-Benz]] would acquire the [[naming rights]] for the stadium, and this was later confirmed by a press conference at the stadium site on August 24. Under the stadium deal with the city of Atlanta and the Georgia World Congress Center Authority, the Falcons organization controls the stadium's naming rights and receives all related revenue. Then-Mercedes-Benz USA CEO Steve Cannon, who would subsequently join the Falcons' organization in 2016 as CEO of AMB Group,<ref>{{cite web|title=Cannon Named CEO of AMB Group|url=http://www.atlantafalcons.com/news/blog/article-1/Cannon-Named-CEO-of-AMB-Group/2522f166-f6c8-4749-bbfd-1485ae59c6b9|publisher=Atlanta Falcons|accessdate=April 24, 2017}}</ref> stated that the sponsorship would last 27 years, calling it the largest marketing deal in Mercedes-Benz' history, but Cannon would not disclose the full value of the deal; however, ''Sports Business Daily'' reported in February 2016 that the naming rights contract was valued at US$324 million. Mercedes-Benz also holds a 10-year naming rights contract for the [[Mercedes-Benz Superdome|Louisiana Superdome]] signed in 2011.<ref name=MB_naming_rights>{{cite news|last1=Tucker|first1=Tim|title=Falcons officially announce Mercedes-Benz as naming rights partner|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/sports/football/falcons-officially-announce-mercedes-benz-as-namin/nnP9Y/|accessdate=August 24, 2015|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lefton |first1=Terry |title=Naming-rights market finds more takers |url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2016/02/22/In-Depth/Naming-Rights.aspx |accessdate=January 6, 2019 |work=Sports Business Daily |date=February 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nTotal sponsorship sales for Mercedes-Benz Stadium have reached $900 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/football/leadoff-falcons-sell-900m-stadium-sponsorships-report-says/KCi2AKCazjeWojJzxNqXCJ/|title=LEADOFF: Falcons sell $900M in stadium sponsorships, report says|last=Tim Tucker|first=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|website=ajc|language=English|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref>\n\nWhile the stadium is owned by the state, it is operated by AMB Group, the parent organization of the Falcons and Atlanta United. All operating profits of Mercedes-Benz Stadium go to AMB Group and not to the state. In addition, AMB Group does not currently pay any property tax on the stadium.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/sep/29/why-are-georgia-taxpayers-paying-700m-for-a-new-nfl-stadium|title=Why are Georgia taxpayers paying $700m for a new NFL stadium?|last=deMause|first=Neil|date=2017-09-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-07-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Major events ==\n\n=== NFL ===\n[[File:SuperBowlLIIIAtlanta.jpg|thumb|Mercedes-Benz Stadium is decorated for [[Super Bowl LIII]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia]]]]\nOn May 19, 2015, Mercedes-Benz Stadium was awarded [[Super Bowl LIII]] in [[2018 NFL season|2019]], marking Atlanta's first time hosting the game since [[Super Bowl XXXIV]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/live-updates-nfl-announcing-sites-for-super-bowls-53-54-55|title=NFL awards future Super Bowls to Atlanta, South Florida and Los Angeles|last=Brinson|first=Will|date=May 24, 2016|accessdate=January 21, 2019|publisher=CBS Sports}}</ref>\n\n===College basketball===\nThe stadium was to host the [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|2020 NCAA Final Four]]. On March 12, 2020 it was completely cancelled outright due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]], though it would have likely shifted to a smaller Atlanta venue (either the [[State Farm Arena]] or the [[McCamish Pavilion]], home of the Final Four's host school, [[Georgia Tech]]) in any case, as the tourney was closed to spectators the day before.<ref name=\"ncaa-covid19\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/e323163560f0429c3be23b38b8fb6d78|title=Only essential staff and limited family at NCAA tournaments|last=Russo|first=Ralph|date=11 March 2020|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=NCAA cancels men's and women's basketball championships due to coronavirus concerns|publisher=NCAA|date=12 March 2020|url=https://www.ncaa.com/live-updates/basketball-men/d1/ncaa-di-mens-and-womens-basketball-tournament-coronavirus-updates/?utm_campaign=hp-rr-links|accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===College and high school football===\n[[File:CollegeFootballPlayoff.jpg|thumb|[[College Football Playoff]] Semifinal (Oklahoma vs LSU) on December 28, 2019]]\nThe [[Peach Bowl]], [[Celebration Bowl]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/college/how-the-celebration-bowl-came-into-existence/YzjeoRMExsgWdoZvMcWykO/|title=How the Celebration Bowl came into existence|last=Sugiura|first=Ken|date=|website=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|language=english|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref> [[SEC Championship Game]], and [[Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/college/future-chick-fil-kickoff-games/FvfiBkJcz1DrdDVsGy8CiO/|title=Future Chick-fil-A Kickoff games|last=|first=|date=|website=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref> moved from the Georgia Dome to Mercedes-Benz Stadium in the [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2017 season]]. The SEC Championship has a long-term deal with Mercedes-Benz Stadium through 2027.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/ncaaf-dr-saturday/chick-fil-a-bowl-adds-peach-back-to-its-name--will-be-one-of-six-semifinal-sites-for-college-football-playoff-185616226.html|title=Chick-fil-A Bowl Adds Peach Back to Its Name, Will Be One of Six Semifinal Sites for College Football Playoff|last=Cooper|first=Sam|date=April 21, 2014|work=[[Yahoo! Sports]]|accessdate=February 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/13601606/sec-championship-game-remain-atlanta-2027|title=SEC Championship Game to remain in Atlanta until 2027|website=ESPN|accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref> On February 26, 2019, it was announced that the [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football|Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets]] had agreed to play one home game annually at Mercedes-Benz Stadium from 2020 through 2024.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/26086173/georgia-tech-play-5-games-mercedes-benz|title=Georgia Tech to play 5 games at Mercedes-Benz|date=2019-02-26|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2018 College Football Playoff National Championship]] was hosted by Atlanta and Mercedes-Benz Stadium. In their first national championship game since 1982, the [[2017 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia Bulldogs]] were defeated in overtime by the [[2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama Crimson Tide]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/football/article/2018-01-08/alabama-vs-georgia-score-crimson-tide-defeat-bulldogs-win-2018-cfp|title=Alabama wins national championship in overtime|last=|first=|date=|website=NCAA.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\nOn December 8, 2017, the stadium hosted the [[Georgia High School Association]] (GHSA) football championship games for Class 1A Private School and Class 3A. The remaining two championship games scheduled for that day, Class 5A and Class 6A, as well as the four games originally scheduled for the next day were postponed and relocated to campus sites due to a major snowstorm to hit Atlanta that weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghsa.net/weather-forces-postponement-saturday-football-finals|title=Weather Forces Postponement of Saturday Football Finals - GHSA.net|website=www.ghsa.net}}</ref> The 2018 GHSA football championships were held on December 11 and 12 due to conflicts with the [[2018 MLS Cup]] on December 8<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghsa.net/football-championships-georgia-farm-bureau-dec-11-12|title=Football Championships by Georgia Farm Bureau on Dec. 11\u201312|publisher=Georgia High School Association|accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref> as well as the [[2018 Celebration Bowl]] scheduled for December 15. In May 2019, the GHSA announced that the football finals would be moved from Mercedes-Benz Stadium to [[Georgia State Stadium]] (a redevelopment of [[Turner Field]]) starting in 2019, citing the higher costs of renting Mercedes-Benz Stadium compared to the former Georgia Dome.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/high-school-sports/ghsa-moves-football-finals-georgia-state/sK9fc2kspX2M5sDt5q7yZN/|title=GHSA moves football finals to Georgia State|last1=Holcomb|first1=Todd|date=May 7, 2019|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Soccer===\n\n*On October 22, 2017, Atlanta United played an MLS regular season match versus [[Toronto FC]] at Mercedes-Benz Stadium in front of 71,874 spectators, beating the record they set for the largest crowd in a stand-alone MLS match in September against [[Orlando City SC|Orlando City]] (which also marked the first time the roof was opened for a soccer game). Atlanta United also set the single-season record for attendance.<ref>[http://www.espnfc.com/atlanta-united-fc/story/3236201/atlanta-united-sets-mls-attendance-records-for-single-season-and-game Atlanta United sets MLS attendance records for single season and game] \u2013 ESPN FC, October 23, 2017</ref>\n*On March 11, 2018, Atlanta United played an MLS regular season match versus [[D.C. United]] at Mercedes-Benz Stadium in front of 72,035 spectators, setting the record for the largest crowd in MLS history.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2018/03/11/atlanta-home-opener-draws-72035-largest-single-game-crowd-mls-history# |title=Atlanta home opener draws 72,035, largest single-game crowd in MLS history|date=March 11, 2018|author=Charles Boehm|access-date=March 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313044919/https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2018/03/11/atlanta-home-opener-draws-72035-largest-single-game-crowd-mls-history# |archive-date=March 13, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n*On October 23, 2017, it was announced that the [[2018 MLS All-Star Game]] would take place at Mercedes-Benz Stadium against Italian club [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]. It was held on August 1, 2018, and set a new record for attendance at an MLS All-Star game, with 72,317 spectators.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/10/23/atlanta-united-host-2018-mls-all-star-game-presented-target# |title=Atlanta United to host 2018 MLS All-Star Game presented by Target|date=October 23, 2017|author=MLSsoccer staff|access-date=October 24, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024212156/https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/10/23/atlanta-united-host-2018-mls-all-star-game-presented-target# |archive-date=October 24, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/sports/atlanta-will-host-2018-mls-all-star-game/C4tFQtYpKUtzckpSfdeZ0H/|title=Atlanta will host 2018 MLS All-Star game|first=Doug|last=Roberson|website=Ajc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Roberson |first=Doug |date=August 1, 2018 |title=Martinez scores but MLS All-Stars fall to Juventus in front of record crowd |url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/martinez-mls-all-stars-tie-juventus-front-record-crowd/7xztCXmW1mO712v99nD8NL/ |work=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref>\n* On December 8, 2018, Atlanta United hosted the [[Portland Timbers]] in the [[2018 MLS Cup]] final (earning home field advantage by virtue of their regular season record over Portland). Atlanta defeated Portland 2\u20130, winning their first-ever MLS championship. The game initially reported a single-game attendance record for Major League Soccer, with 73,019 spectators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/atlanta-sets-mls-cup-attendance-record/lJVEXg0pSHjtlNJ7TM06hK/|title=Atlanta United sets MLS Cup attendance record|last=Doug|first=Roberson|website=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|language=English|access-date=December 22, 2018}}</ref>\n*On August 14, 2019, Atlanta United hosted [[Club Am\u00e9rica]] in the [[2019 Campeones Cup]]. Atlanta defeated Am\u00e9rica 3\u20132, winning their first-ever Campeones Cup in front of 40,128 supporters. This attendance set an attendance record for Campeones Cup. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2019/08/14/atlanta-united-3-club-america-2-2019-campeones-cup-match-recap|title=Atlanta United 3, Club America 2 {{!}} 2019 Campeones Cup Match Recap|last=Butler|first=Dylan}}</ref>\n\n===Concerts===\nOn October 12, 2017, the inaugural concert at Mercedes-Benz Stadium, featuring Garth Brooks, received widespread scorn, including demands for refunds, due to the reported abysmal acoustics that many attendees deemed unfit for concert sound. The stadium authority stated that plans are underway to help improve the acoustical quality of the stadium.<ref>{{cite web |title=Garth Brooks fans complained of audio issue during first concert at Mercedes-Benz Stadium |url=http://www.ajc.com/news/local/audio-issues-plague-garth-brooks-fans-during-first-concert-mercedes-benz-stadium/z3mfFzunCZkNEw4iXN0iJN/|website=Ajc.com|accessdate=April 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince the first concert, efforts were made to improve the acoustics in the stadium. New speakers were added to suites, the angle of the bowl speakers was adjusted and delays introduced in order to reduce echo. During a concert in May 2018 featuring Kenny Chesney, reports were that the sound quality had improved since the first concert.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mercedes-Benz Stadium officials confident of sound fixes for Kenny Chesney concert|url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/music/mercedes-benz-stadium-officials-confident-sound-fixes-for-kenny-chesney-concert/E0DYqfMvYpjPCDjLW8kyNM/|website=Ajc.com|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Concert review: Kenny Chesney, Thomas Rhett performed with (mostly) improved sound at Mercedes-Benz Stadium|url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/music/concert-review-kenny-chesney-thomas-rhett-performed-with-mostly-improved-sound-mercedes-benz-stadium/EoloQVVpicsjTcepxp85NM/|website=Ajc.com|accessdate=November 23, 2018}}</ref> Chesney's concert attracted 51,312 people and grossed $5.068 million.<ref>{{cite web |title=Current Boxscore |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529133610/https://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore/|website=web.archive.org|accessdate=February 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing concerts by Garth Brooks and Kenny Chesney, the venue hosted [[Taylor Swift]] for two nights in August 2018 as part of [[Taylor Swift's Reputation Stadium Tour]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Taylor Swift reputation Stadium Tour |url=https://mercedesbenzstadium.com/taylor-swift-reputation-stadium-tour/|website=mercedesbenzstadium.com|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref> Over the two sold-out nights, Taylor performed to an audience of 116,746 people and grossed $18.089 million.<ref>{{cite web |title=Current Boxscore |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180817081748/https://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore/|website=web.archive.org|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref> She was the first music act to headline the stadium for two consecutive nights.<ref>{{cite web |title=Taylor Swift plays for more that 115,000 in Atlanta |url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/music/taylor-swift-plays-for-more-than-115-atlanta/hoPYFvkns3HQpdylYFK0LN/|website=Ajc.com|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlso in August 2018, [[Beyonc\u00e9]] and [[Jay-Z]] performed for two nights as part of the [[On the Run II Tour]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Jay-Z and Beyonc\u00e9 Announce Additional OTR II Tour Dates Due to Overwhelming Demand |url=https://mercedesbenzstadium.com/jay-z-beyonce-announce-additional-otr-ii-tour-dates-due-overwhelming-demand/|website=mercedesbenzstadium.com|accessdate=February 5, 2019}}</ref> The two shows grossed $14.074 million and were attended by 105,170 people.<ref>{{cite web |title=Current Boxscore |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911075716/https://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore/|website=web.archive.org|accessdate=February 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Ed Sheeran]] performed at the venue as part of his [[\u00f7 Tour]] in November 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ed Sheeran |url=https://mercedesbenzstadium.com/ed-sheeran/|website=mercedesbenzstadium.com|accessdate=February 5, 2019}}</ref> The show was attended by 50,906 people and grossed $5.021 million.<ref>{{cite web |title=Current Boxscore |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181113224629/https://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore/|website=web.archive.org|accessdate=February 5, 2019}}</ref> This show marked the end of the 2018 leg of the tour, which was billed as the Top Tour of 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Year in Touring Charts: Ed Sheeran Claims 2018's Top Tour; Taylor Swift, Beyonc\u00e9 & Jay-Z Do Big Business|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/year-in-music-2018/8488851/touring-charts-year-ed-sheeran-tops-taylor-swift-beyonce|website=billboard.com|accessdate=June 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, [[George Strait]] performed a one-off concert at the venue, joined by musical guests [[Chris Stapleton]], [[Chris Janson]], and Ashley McBryde.<ref>{{cite web |title=George Strait |url=https://mercedesbenzstadium.com/events/george-strait/|website=mercedesbenzstadium.com|accessdate=February 5, 2019}}</ref> The concert was attended by 55,255 people, and grossed $11.9 million.<ref>{{cite web |title=Current Boxscore |url= https://www.billboard.com/biz/current-boxscore|website=billboard.com|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref> This became the highest grossing single night concert in the venue's history, and became George Strait's third show to earn over $10 million.<ref>{{cite web |title=George Strait Breaks Boxscore Records With $12.7 Million Haul at RodeoHouston |url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8507560/george-strait-breaks-boxscore-records-rodeohouston|website=billboard.com|accessdate=June 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Other major events===\n\n*On March 3, 2018, the stadium hosted a round of the [[AMA Supercross Championship]], replacing the Georgia Dome which had been part of the schedule since 1993.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ultimatemotorcycling.com/2018/03/04/2018-atlanta-supercross-results-coverage-fast-facts-video/|title=Spoilers: Atlanta Supercross Results and Coverage|date=March 4, 2018|work=Ultimate Motorcycling|access-date=April 6, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*On November 15, 2014, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] announced Mercedes-Benz Stadium will hold the [[Final Four (college basketball)|men's college basketball Final Four]] in 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/sports/college/atlanta-lands-final-four-in-2020/nh7ZZ/|title=Atlanta Lands Final Four in 2020|last=Tucker|first=Tim|date=November 14, 2014|newspaper=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|accessdate=February 5, 2015}}</ref>\n*On July 28, 2018, the stadium hosted the [[Drum Corps International]] Southeastern Championship which was previously held in the [[Georgia Dome]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dci.org/news/mercedes-benz-stadium-expected-to-host-18-dci-southeastern-championship|title=Mercedes-Benz Stadium expected to host '18 DCI Southeastern Championship|website=DCI.org|accessdate=July 30, 2018}}</ref>\n*On December 31, 2019 \u2013 January 2, 2020, Mercedes-Benz Stadium hosted its first ever [[Passion Conferences]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Parke |first1=Caleb |title=At Passion 2019, students raise $400G to translate Bible for deaf people across world |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/passion-2019-students-raise-over-400k-to-share-gospel-with-160000-unreached-people-in-16-countries |accessdate=February 7, 2019 |work=Fox News |date=January 4, 2019}}</ref> The event made history by becoming the largest youth-centered Christian conference ever held in the United States with 65,000 people in attendance. It is higher than Passion's 2017 event in the Georgia Dome, which held an estimated 50,000 people. {{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n*On January 4, 2018, the stadium was the subject of the premiere episode of ''Building Giants'' on [[Science Channel]]. Using footage of the construction along with [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]], the building process is explored in detail. It was noted during the episode that the heaviest truss sections were erected by the largest conventional crawler crane ever built in North America, a Manitowoc Model 31000 which is rated at a capacity of 2,535 US Tons.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nordyke|first1=Kimberly|title=Science Channel Adds Two Series on Superstructures and Extreme Machines (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/science-channel-adds-two-series-superstructures-extreme-machines-1066098|accessdate=January 5, 2018|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=December 11, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n*A train horn blares after every Falcons and United score and win \u2013 a nod to Atlanta's railroad history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thefalconswire.usatoday.com/2017/09/19/why-the-falcons-play-a-train-horn-at-mercedes-benz-stadium/|title=Why the Falcons play a train horn at Mercedes-Benz Stadium|author1=Scott Carasik|publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=September 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://bloggingdirty.com/2017/09/22/mercedes-benz-stadiums-train-horn-is-awesome/|title=Mercedes-Benz Stadium\u2019s Train Horn is Awesome|author1=Adnan Ikic|publisher=[[Fansided]]|date=September 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Truist Park]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat|Mercedes-Benz Stadium}}\n*{{Official website|http://mercedesbenzstadium.com/}}\n\n{{s-start-collapsible|header={{s-sta|et}}}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the [[Atlanta Falcons]]\n | years = 2017\u2013present\n | before = [[Georgia Dome]]\n | after = none\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of [[Atlanta United FC]]\n | years = 2017\u2013present\n | before = [[Bobby Dodd Stadium]]\n | after = none\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[College Football Playoff National Championship]]\n | years = 2018\n | before = [[Raymond James Stadium]]\n | after = [[Levi's Stadium]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the [[Chick-Fil-A]] [[Peach Bowl]]\n | years = 2017\u2013present\n | before = Georgia Dome\n | after = none\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the [[SEC Championship Game]]\n | years = 2017\u2013present\n | before = Georgia Dome\n | after = none\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Host of<br />[[Super Bowl LIII]]\n | years = 2019\n | before = [[U.S. Bank Stadium]]\n | after = [[Hard Rock Stadium]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n|title=[[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|NCAA Men's Division I]]<br />[[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|Basketball Tournament]]<br />Finals Venue\n| years = 2020\n| before = [[U.S. Bank Stadium]]\n| after = [[Lucas Oil Stadium]]\n}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Atlanta Falcons}}\n{{Atlanta United FC}}\n{{Major Lea